Europe needs a migration reboot.
Brussels — Over 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
At the same time, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking spent the entire summer searching for a safe port where the passengers on board could disembark.
Refugee and migrant camps on Lesbos Island in Greece are overcrowded, and the conditions in other安置 camps in Libya are similarly dire.
Turkey violated the 2016 agreement that was meant to prevent immigrants from entering the EU.
Although Europe wants to help immigrants and respects international law, it does not want to be overcrowded.
In 2015–16, the number of refugees and immigrants entering the EU surged—many fleeing the Syrian conflict—greatly affecting trust within the EU.
Massive immigration inflows have eroded the government's confidence in managing the EU's external borders and asylum policies, and have highlighted the ineffectiveness of cooperation with immigration source countries.
Therefore, immigration has become a political football, a favorite tool of populists.
Under the leadership of President von der Leyen, the new European Commission must regain control over migration issues while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
For this reason, the EU needs to revise its policies in four areas and mobilize member states to take action in the interest of Europe.
First, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, which is a prerequisite for maintaining open internal borders.
Any country in which the people can move freely within its territory, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, will not outsource control of its external borders to a state or region.
Controlling the external borders of the EU is both a collective task and a national task.
The European Border and Coast Guard Agency, Frontex, must be further strengthened and should deploy joint guard units with member states — including along coastlines and at airports.
The EU also has to restart Operation Sophia to combat illegal immigration in the Mediterranean.
Secondly, Europe needs to handle economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Confusing them has already brought the asylum system close to collapse; addressing them separately helps ensure that immigrants concerned about their safety can speak out while their rights are protected.
Addressing the real economic and social needs of the EU requires an effective blue card or green card policy targeting economic migrants, along with the implementation of an overall immigration target.
This cannot wait for the next immigration crisis to consider introducing these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboo.
First, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a matter of common interest.
Secondly, policies must clearly define which immigrants are welcome.
Third, member states must answer the question of what kind of EU assistance is needed to achieve a smooth migration process.
Finally, visas and work permits must be addressed to facilitate the return of undocumented immigrants to their home countries.
Indeed, according to the EU treaties, each member state is responsible for managing immigration from outside the EU on its own.
However, it would be a major step forward if the government reached an agreement on the overall EU immigration targets.
In contrast, member states can specify the economic immigration source countries and specific requirements they desire, as well as the EU budget resources needed to accommodate them.
In this way, the right to accept immigrants would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has long implemented an active immigration policy, selecting immigrants based on indicators such as country of origin, skill level, and age group.
Europe can also do this.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First, the one-size-fits-all approach to the compulsory distribution of asylum seekers within the EU must be abandoned.
This requirement undermines the atmosphere within the EU, but it could still be feasible if the border, asylum, and immigration systems are fully effective.
Moreover, one cannot expect the leading member states of the EU to solve the problem of illegal immigration crossing external borders on their own.
The安置营 is already overcrowded, with immigrants suffering abuse from the authorities or being driven northward.
The responsibility of the first member state that the immigrants arrive at must be supplemented by the EU's cohesion policy.
The EU must also provide experts and funds to improve the capacity of national asylum authorities to act and manage effectively.
Only in this way can national decisions be respected throughout the Schengen Area, ensuring the integrity of the cross-border travel zone.
After clarifying the actions and management capabilities of the national protection authorities, the process for handling asylum applications can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should build stronger win-win cooperation with source countries and transit countries.
These connections are crucial for repatriating immigrants who are legally prohibited from entering the EU back to their countries of origin.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as initiatives in security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's immigration targets and skills cooperation aimed at preparing for European jobs can provide stable remittances to third countries.
At the same time, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes the population explosion in Sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and a lack of job opportunities.
EU aid should focus on reshaping stability and reducing risks by supporting security, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in this area can make investments safer, release private and domestic financial resources, thereby achieving national economic growth, job creation, and providing an alternative to immigration.
The new European Commission has the opportunity to move the EU away from its instinctive reactions to the migration crisis toward a more consistent and sustained approach, both internally and externally.
We must never miss the opportunity.
